The paper deals with task execution and prioritization in robotic applications, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The use of optimization techniques and control barrier functions suggests a systems and control (cs.SY) aspect to the work. The paper also mentions the possibility of changing objectives over time, which could involve machine learning (cs.LG) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI) techniques. Finally, the application of the proposed approach to a robotic manipulator suggests a computer vision (cs.CV) aspect to the work.
